column5:
thank you all for the info. very helpful! rice is pretty integral to my family history. i have a family legacy of growing rice here in california, and have fond memories of my childhood and visiting my grandparents farm. so being in vietnam, to try and land myself in the country to see different stages is certainly an aim. while i grew up in the bay area, and am ultimately a city person, i spent many years growing up in the sierra nevadas as well. so hill country and the mountains are also a must.
@scott
thanks for the info, i am sure it will be stunning either way! and yes, part of the plan was ninh binh and pu luong would be in a different stage all together. glad to know i will be within target for that :)
@michael
i unfortunately do not drive, so motorbike is definitely out of the question. most likely bus, private car, or a combo of the two, would be my route of travel (have been considering hoang su phi lodge, and one of their trekking packages). thanks for the info on weather in general for the area, and that of your experience in july. good to know regarding mu cang chai as well. that has also been in consideration (recommendations in detail there would certainly be helpful). for my time, the ha giang loop was not really factored into my itinerary, even though i know it is one of the major draws to the region. perhaps i will reevaluate that.
@john
maybe the end of may might be better to aim for. i could flip my itinerary around and go south to north in this case. my work schedule limits me to travel within the month, and not straddling two. this year i have already factored not be an option, so looking toward 2022 for this. i was starting to plan my trip to vietnam back in 2019, but jumped on an opportunity to go to the philippines with a friend instead, and had a fantastic time (my first intro to se asia). we basically were in ph when covid went into a full scale pandemic, and had some trouble getting home in mid feb due to lockdowns and travel bans. we were very lucky. congrats on your first dose of the vaccine! and yes, hopefully we can all look forward to when travel can resume.
i suppose i have some time to translate the farmers almanac and get a little more acquainted :)
thank you all for your contributions, and certainly have seen other insights from you in other areas of the forum. very much appreciated!
